headline.main-hed: Tunisia’s Landmark Presidential Election Rekindles Fears
headline.deck: Poll Expected to Bring 87-Year-Old Politician Who Served Under Autocratic Regimes to Power

media.media-caption: Tunisia held a landmark presidential election Sunday, but the expected frontrunner, an 87-year-old who served under two autocrats, rekindles fears of old regimes. WSJ's Tamer El-Ghobashy reports.

article-body.p: SIDI BOUZID, Tunisia—In this city where the Arab Spring was born, an undercurrent of anxiety accompanied the country’s first democratic presidential election on Sunday.

Outside the cosmopolitan coastal capital of Tunis, front-runner Beji Caid Essebsi, an 87-year-old politician who served under two autocratic regimes, is viewed with suspicion. He is seen as an unsettling relic of the autocratic regimes that ruled Tunisia from its independence from France in 1956 until the 2010 uprising.
“You can’t be stung by the same scorpion twice,” said Najib Issaoui, a 27-year-old fruit vendor in a small market in the center of Sidi Bouzid. “The revolution is in progress. But it isn’t finished.”

inset.p: After a 50-year era of darkness, we are able to choose who represents us.

article-body.p: Mr. Issaoui occupies a stall near the one that once belonged to another fruit vendor, Mohamed Bouazizi. In December 2010, Mr. Bouazizi set himself on fire after local police confiscated his wares because his scales weren’t properly certified.

His self-immolation in front of the city’s municipal headquarters rocked the nation and rippled across the region. Soon came local labor strikes and protests that spread to the capital Tunis. The uprising sent longtime Tunisian dictator Zine El Abidine Ben Ali fleeing to Saudi Arabia, where he remains.
In short order, Tunisians’ cries of “The people demand the fall of the regime” spread to Egypt, Libya, Yemen and Syria.

Sunday’s vote marked the first democratic presidential election in Tunisia’s history, completing a nearly four-year transition that followed the toppling of Mr. Ben Ali. Mr. Essebsi is widely expected to defeat 21 other candidates after his secular party, Nida Tunis, wrested control of parliament from moderate Islamist party Ennahda in last month’s legislative elections.
Tunisia’s election authority said about 65% of eligible voters turned out for the vote—a small decline from a nearly 69% turnout in the parliamentary ballot.

Residents of Sidi Bouzid said their fervor for holding the powerful accountable hasn’t waned. Tunisians insist that the same attributes that helped their country avoid civil war, military coups and a shift toward political Islam over nearly four years will also check the power of the future president.

Mr. Essebsi’s success would underscore how the political winds have shifted in Tunisia—and the region at large—since Islamists gained control after the uprising. Tunisia has had an interim president elected by parliament since then. Ennahda led the moderate Islamist government that came to power following the uprising. But the party initially resisted sharing power and sought to put an Islamist stamp on the constitution. It was widely criticized for not reining in Salafist extremists who battled security forces in the country’s border regions. Ennahda was also seen as sluggish in addressing the country’s flatlining economy. In campaigning for parliament and the presidency, Nida Tunis characterized Islamism as alien to the Tunisian national character and seized on a nostalgia for the stability that autocrats offered. Mr. Essebsi has billed himself as an experienced statesman, appealing to voters weary of years of transition.

media.media-caption: A man at a polling station in Tunis on Sunday prepares to vote.

article-body.p: Unemployment is running at 15%—and among youth at 30%. Tunisian Interior Ministry officials say that poor job picture is one major catalyst for Tunisians accounting for the highest number of foreign fighters joining extremist groups in Syria and Iraq.
As frustrations grew with the pace of transition and with little tangible improvement in quality of life, voters last month gave Mr. Essebsi’s party a plurality in parliamentary elections.

list.list-item: Dec. 17, 2010 Protests over unemployment and political restrictions spread after a street vendor sets himself on fire to protest being humiliated by police
Jan. 17, 2011 President Ben Ali flees the country to Saudi Arabia amid continuing protests.
October 2011 Islamist party Ennahda wins first Constituent Assembly elections but falls short of an outright majority.
December 2011 Human rights activist Mohamed Moncef Marzouki is elected interim president by the Constituent Assembly and Ennahda’s Hamadi Jebali is sworn in as prime minister.
February 2013 After assassination of leftist leader Chokri Belaid prompts social unrest, Prime Minister Jebali resigns.
July 2013 Assassination of opposition politician Mohamed Brahmi triggers mass demonstrations, a general strike and calls for the government to resign.
October 2013 Ennahda agrees to hand over power to a caretaker government tasked with organizing fresh elections in 2014.
January 2014 Parliament passes the country’s first post-revolutionary constitution. New prime minister Mehdi Jomaa forms interim cabinet of independents and technocrats.
October 2014 Nida Tunis, a party gathering secularists, union activists, leftists, liberals and old-regime figures, wins largest number of seats in the parliamentary elections. --Radhouane Addala

media.media-caption: Security officers stand outside a polling station in Tunis on Sunday during Tunisia’s first presidential election since the Arab Spring revolution.

article-body.p: Once the presidential race is decided, Tunisia will have its first executive and legislature with a five-year mandate.
And despite his party winning 86 of the 217 seats in Parliament, it will have to contend with a still viable Ennahda, which won 69 seats and is poised to become a formidable opposition.

“This election will decide if we fall into a well of instability or if we will save the country,” said Reem Howeidi, a 34-year-old homemaker who was voting on Sunday in a downtown Tunis polling station with her parents.
Her young daughter stood by her side, holding a Tunisian flag.
She said she was voting for Mr. Essebsi, seeing him as the candidate best equipped to usher in the political and economic stability she wants.
“He is the only one with the experience required,” she said. “We can trust him.”

Mr. Essebsi, who will turn 88 this week, has served as head of Parliament, interior minister, defense minister and foreign minister, under the old regimes of Habib Bourguiba and Mr. Ben Ali. Mr. Bourguiba led Tunisia’s independence movement from France and is seen as the founder of the modern Tunisian state. His rule was marked by political repression and he was ousted by Mr. Ben Ali in a bloodless coup in 1987.

About 155 miles south of Tunis, the main boulevard in Sidi Bouzid has been renamed after Mr. Bouazizi and a large portrait of him hangs over the central post office. Nearby is a sculpture of an unmanned fruit cart.

In many ways, Mr. Issaoui, the fruit vendor, embodies the frustrations that led to the uprising. He is a university-educated physical education teacher who has beenforced into vending by a lack of employment opportunities.

“Nothing has changed in my life,” he said. “But I’m optimistic because we have a system now that lets us choose our leader. And if he doesn’t deliver, we will be the ground zero for change again. Fear doesn’t exist here anymore.”
Fellow vendor Sami Alifi, 26, sought to clarify that he and others would respect the vote no matter the outcome.
“But if Essebsi is elected, I’ll be first one in the street,” he said. “Not to overthrow him. That’s not democracy, but to keep the pressure on him.”
Both men said they support challenger Mohamed Hechmi Hamdi, a son of Sidi Bouzid who is seen as one of the longest shots for the presidency.

“They accuse us of provincialism for voting for someone from our community,” Mr. Alifi said, referring to political commentary that is typical of the coastal cities of Tunis and Sfax. “But who is it that is really provincial when they can’t even nominate someone from outside the ancient political elite?”
article-body.tagline: Radhouane Addala contributed to this article.
